What is a Locator?

A locator is a way to identify elements on a webpage (like buttons, input fields, links) so Selenium can interact with them.

Types of Locators in Selenium

Selenium provides 8 types of locators:

1Ô∏è‚É£ id

Finds an element using its unique ID attribute.

Most preferred because it‚Äôs fast and unique.

driver.findElement(By.id("username")).sendKeys("admin");

2Ô∏è‚É£ name

Finds an element using its name attribute.

Can be used if ID is missing, but name may not be unique.

driver.findElement(By.name("password")).sendKeys("12345");

3Ô∏è‚É£ className

Finds elements using the class attribute.

Can return multiple elements if the class is used multiple times.


What are XPath Axes?

XPath axes are directions to traverse the DOM relative to the current node.

Think of it as giving Selenium a path to move around: parent, child, sibling, ancestor, etc.

Common XPath Axes in Selenium
Axis	Meaning	Example
child	Selects direct children of the current node	//div[@id='login']/child::input
parent	Selects the parent of the current node	//input[@id='username']/parent::div
ancestor	Selects all ancestors (parent, grandparent, etc.)	//input[@id='username']/ancestor::form
descendant	Selects all descendants (children, grandchildren)	//div[@id='login']/descendant::input
following	Selects everything after the current node in the DOM	//label[@for='username']/following::input[1]
following-sibling	Selects all siblings after the current node	//label[@for='username']/following-sibling::input
preceding	Selects everything before the current node in the DOM	//input[@id='password']/preceding::label
preceding-sibling	Selects all siblings before the current node	//input[@id='password']/preceding-sibling::label
self	Refers to the current node itself	//input[@id='username']/self::input
descendant-or-self	Current node + all descendants	//div[@id='login']/descendant-or-self::input
Examples in Selenium
1Ô∏è‚É£ Using parent axis
driver.findElement(By.xpath("//input[@id='username']/parent::div"));


Finds the <div> that contains the input.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Using following-sibling axis
driver.findElement(By.xpath("//label[text()='Username']/following-sibling::input"));


Finds the input next to the label.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Using ancestor axis
driver.findElement(By.xpath("//input[@id='username']/ancestor::form"));


Finds the <form> containing the input.

get() method

Used to open a URL in the browser.

Waits for the page to fully load before performing the next command.

Simple and most commonly used.

Syntax
driver.get("https://example.com");

Key points

Equivalent to entering the URL in the browser‚Äôs address bar.

Cannot do additional browser navigation (back, forward) directly.

2Ô∏è‚É£ navigate().to() method

Also used to open a URL.

Part of the Navigation interface (driver.navigate()).

Can be used along with:

back() ‚Üí go back

forward() ‚Üí go forward

refresh() ‚Üí reload page

Syntax
driver.navigate().to("https://example.com");

Key points

Can accept a URL or a java.net.URL object.

More flexible for browser history navigation.

Side-by-side comparison
Feature	get()	navigate().to()
Purpose	Open a URL	Open a URL / Navigate forward/back/refresh
Page load	Waits until fully loaded	Usually waits, but less strict
Browser navigation	No	Yes (back(), forward(), refresh())
Syntax	driver.get("url")	driver.navigate().to("url")
Use case	Simple URL opening	Complex navigation / history management
Example using navigate()
driver.navigate().to("https://example.com"); // open URL
driver.navigate().refresh();                  // refresh page
driver.navigate().back();                     // go back
driver.navigate().forward();                  // go forward

Interview-ready answer (one-liner)

"get() is used to open a URL and waits for the page to load, while navigate().to() can also open a URL but is mainly used for advanced browser navigation like back, forward, and refresh."


close() method

Closes the current browser window that WebDriver is controlling.

If multiple windows/tabs are open, other windows remain open.

WebDriver session does NOT end if other windows are open.

Syntax
driver.close();

Example
WebDriver driver = new ChromeDriver();
driver.get("https://example.com");

// Open a new tab/window
driver.switchTo().newWindow(WindowType.TAB);
driver.get("https://google.com");

// Close current window (Google)
driver.close(); 

// Original window (example.com) is still open

2Ô∏è‚É£ quit() method

Closes all browser windows opened by the WebDriver.

Ends the WebDriver session completely.

After quit(), trying to use the driver will throw SessionNotFoundException.

Syntax
driver.quit();


getText()

Returns the visible text of a web element on the page.

Ignores hidden elements or attributes.

Usually used for labels, buttons, links, messages.

Syntax
String text = element.getText();

Example
<button id="loginBtn">Login</button>

WebElement button = driver.findElement(By.id("loginBtn"));
String text = button.getText();  // Returns "Login"


Key point: Only retrieves what the user sees on the page.

2Ô∏è‚É£ getAttribute()

Returns the value of a specified attribute of an element.

Can retrieve value, id, name, href, class, type, etc.

Often used for input fields, links, hidden elements, and custom attributes.

Syntax
String attr = element.getAttribute("attributeName");

Example
<input id="username" type="text" value="admin">

WebElement input = driver.findElement(By.id("username"));
String value = input.getAttribute("value"); // Returns "admin"
String type = input.getAttribute("type");   // Returns "text"


What is an Alert?

Alerts are pop-up boxes that appear on a webpage.

Types of alerts:

Simple Alert ‚Äì only OK button

Confirm Alert ‚Äì OK and Cancel buttons

Prompt Alert ‚Äì OK, Cancel, and an input field

These alerts are JavaScript pop-ups, so Selenium cannot interact with them using normal findElement().

2Ô∏è‚É£ Switching to Alert

Before interacting with an alert, you must switch WebDriver focus to it.

Alert alert = driver.switchTo().alert();


driver.switchTo().alert() returns an Alert object.

Now you can interact with the alert.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Interacting with Alerts
Action	Method	Description
Accept / OK	alert.accept()	Clicks the OK button
Dismiss / Cancel	alert.dismiss()	Clicks the Cancel button
Get text	alert.getText()	Reads the alert message
Send text	alert.sendKeys("text")	Enters text (only for prompt alerts)
Examples
1Ô∏è‚É£ Simple Alert
driver.findElement(By.id("simpleAlertBtn")).click();

// Switch to alert
Alert alert = driver.switchTo().alert();

// Get text
System.out.println(alert.getText());

// Click OK
alert.accept();

2Ô∏è‚É£ Confirm Alert
driver.findElement(By.id("confirmAlertBtn")).click();
Alert alert = driver.switchTo().alert();

// Click Cancel
alert.dismiss();

3Ô∏è‚É£ Prompt Alert
driver.findElement(By.id("promptAlertBtn")).click();
Alert alert = driver.switchTo().alert();

// Enter text
alert.sendKeys("Selenium");

// Click OK
alert.accept();

4Ô∏è‚É£ Going back to main page

After interacting with an alert, WebDriver automatically returns to the main page, so usually no extra step is needed.

If you want to explicitly check, you can switch back to default content:

driver.switchTo().defaultContent();


What is a Frame?

A frame or iframe is an HTML element that embeds another HTML document inside the main page.

Elements inside a frame are isolated from the main page, so Selenium cannot interact with them directly.

2Ô∏è‚É£ How to handle frames

Selenium provides three ways to switch to a frame:

By index

By name or ID

By WebElement

Step 1: Switch to frame
1Ô∏è‚É£ By index

Index starts from 0.

Example: Switch to the first frame on the page

driver.switchTo().frame(0);

2Ô∏è‚É£ By name or ID
driver.switchTo().frame("frameName");
driver.switchTo().frame("frameID");

3Ô∏è‚É£ By WebElement
WebElement frameElement = driver.findElement(By.xpath("//iframe[@id='frame1']"));
driver.switchTo().frame(frameElement);

Step 2: Interact with elements inside the frame

Once inside, you can interact normally:

driver.findElement(By.id("insideFrameButton")).click();

Step 3: Go back to main page

After finishing, you must switch back to the main page to interact with elements outside the frame.

1Ô∏è‚É£ Switch to parent frame

Goes one level up

driver.switchTo().parentFrame();

2Ô∏è‚É£ Switch to main page

Goes all the way back to the main content

driver.switchTo().defaultContent();

Step 4: Handling nested frames

For frames inside frames, switch step by step:

driver.switchTo().frame("outerFrame");
driver.switchTo().frame("innerFrame");
driver.findElement(By.id("btn")).click();

// Go back to outer frame
driver.switchTo().parentFrame();

// Go back to main page
driver.switchTo().defaultContent();

Pro Tips

Always switch to the frame first, otherwise NoSuchElementException.

Use WebElement method if frames don‚Äôt have name or ID.

Check nested frames using driver.findElements(By.tagName("iframe")).

Interview-ready answer

‚ÄúIn Selenium, to handle frames, first switch to the frame using driver.switchTo().frame() (by index, name/ID, or WebElement). After interacting with elements inside the frame, use driver.switchTo().parentFrame() to go one level up or driver.switchTo().defaultContent() to return to the main page.‚Äù

What is a Window or Tab?

Modern web apps often open links or pop-ups in new windows or tabs.

Selenium cannot interact with a new window directly until you switch focus to it.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Step 1: Get Window Handles

Every window/tab has a unique ID called a window handle.
You can get them using:

String mainWindow = driver.getWindowHandle(); // current window
Set<String> allWindows = driver.getWindowHandles(); // all open windows


getWindowHandle() ‚Üí returns current window ID

getWindowHandles() ‚Üí returns all window IDs as a Set

3Ô∏è‚É£ Step 2: Switch to the new window/tab

Use a loop to find the window you want:

for (String window : allWindows) {
    if (!window.equals(mainWindow)) {
        driver.switchTo().window(window);
        break;
    }
}


Now WebDriver focuses on the new window.

You can interact with elements there.

4Ô∏è‚É£ Step 3: Perform actions in new window
driver.findElement(By.id("submit")).click();

5Ô∏è‚É£ Step 4: Go back to main window

After finishing, switch back to the original window:

driver.switchTo().window(mainWindow);


Types of Waits in Selenium

There are three main waits:

A) Implicit Wait

Applies globally for the lifetime of WebDriver.

Selenium will poll the DOM for a set time before throwing NoSuchElementException.

Simple and less flexible.

Syntax
driver.manage().timeouts().implicitlyWait(Duration.ofSeconds(10));

Key points

Applied once and affects all element searches.

Polls DOM automatically.

Does not wait for specific conditions.

B) Explicit Wait

Waits for a specific condition for a specific element.

More flexible and powerful than implicit wait.

Uses WebDriverWait and ExpectedConditions.

Syntax
WebDriverWait wait = new WebDriverWait(driver, Duration.ofSeconds(10));
WebElement element = wait.until(ExpectedConditions.visibilityOfElementLocated(By.id("loginBtn")));
element.click();

Key points

Works for specific elements.

Can wait for conditions like:

visibilityOfElementLocated

elementToBeClickable

alertIsPresent

Throws TimeoutException if condition not met.

C) Fluent Wait

Advanced version of explicit wait.

Allows you to specify:

Maximum wait time

Polling interval

Ignored exceptions (like NoSuchElementException)

Great for dynamic pages where elements appear irregularly.

Syntax
Wait<WebDriver> wait = new FluentWait<>(driver)
    .withTimeout(Duration.ofSeconds(20))
    .pollingEvery(Duration.ofSeconds(2))
    .ignoring(NoSuchElementException.class);

WebElement element = wait.until(ExpectedConditions.visibilityOfElementLocated(By.id("loginBtn")));
element.click();

Key points

More customizable than explicit wait.

Polls the DOM at custom intervals.

Can ignore exceptions during wait.


ypes of Dropdowns in Selenium

Static Dropdown (HTML <select> tag)

The options are hard-coded in HTML.

Selenium provides the Select class to handle them.

Dynamic/Custom Dropdown (Non-<select> tag)

Options are created dynamically with JavaScript.

Cannot use Select class ‚Äî use WebElement clicks or loops.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Handling Static Dropdowns (<select> tag)
Step 1: Import Select class
import org.openqa.selenium.support.ui.Select;

Step 2: Locate the dropdown
WebElement dropdown = driver.findElement(By.id("country"));

Step 3: Create Select object
Select select = new Select(dropdown);

Step 4: Select options

By visible text

select.selectByVisibleText("India");


By index

select.selectByIndex(2); // third option


By value

select.selectByValue("IN");

Step 5: Get all options
List<WebElement> allOptions = select.getOptions();
for(WebElement option : allOptions) {
    System.out.println(option.getText());
}

3Ô∏è‚É£ Handling Dynamic / Custom Dropdowns (Non-<select> tag)

Dynamic dropdowns require manual click operations:

Example HTML
<div class="dropdown">
  <button>Choose Country</button>
  <ul>
    <li>India</li>
    <li>USA</li>
    <li>UK</li>
  </ul>
</div>

Selenium Code
// Click dropdown to expand options
driver.findElement(By.xpath("//button[text()='Choose Country']")).click();

// Get all options
List<WebElement> options = driver.findElements(By.xpath("//ul/li"));

// Loop and select
for(WebElement option : options) {
    if(option.getText().equals("USA")) {
        option.click();
        break;
    }
}

4Ô∏è‚É£ Multi-select Dropdowns

Use Select class and check isMultiple()

Select select = new Select(driver.findElement(By.id("fruits")));
if(select.isMultiple()) {
    select.selectByIndex(0);
    select.selectByValue("apple");
    select.selectByVisibleText("Orange");
    select.deselectAll(); // Deselect all if needed
}

5Ô∏è‚É£ Interview-ready answer

‚ÄúFor static dropdowns with <select> tags, Selenium provides the Select class which can select options by index, value, or visible text. For dynamic or custom dropdowns built with JavaScript, we locate the dropdown and options as WebElements, click to expand, and then loop through the options to select the desired one.‚Äù


What is the Actions Class?

The Actions class in Selenium is used to perform complex user interactions like:

Mouse hover

Right click (context click)

Double click

Drag and drop

Click and hold

Located in:

import org.openqa.selenium.interactions.Actions;

2Ô∏è‚É£ How to use the Actions class
Step 1: Create Actions object
Actions actions = new Actions(driver);

Step 2: Perform action on a WebElement

Most actions require build().perform() at the end to execute.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Common Mouse Actions
A) Mouse Hover (Move to element)
WebElement menu = driver.findElement(By.id("menu"));
actions.moveToElement(menu).build().perform();


Hover over an element to reveal dropdowns or tooltips.

B) Right Click (Context Click)
WebElement element = driver.findElement(By.id("rightClickBtn"));
actions.contextClick(element).build().perform();

C) Double Click
WebElement button = driver.findElement(By.id("doubleClickBtn"));
actions.doubleClick(button).build().perform();

D) Drag and Drop
WebElement source = driver.findElement(By.id("drag"));
WebElement target = driver.findElement(By.id("drop"));

actions.dragAndDrop(source, target).build().perform();


Alternative: Click and hold ‚Üí move ‚Üí release

actions.clickAndHold(source).moveToElement(target).release().build().perform();

E) Click and Hold / Move
actions.clickAndHold(source)
       .moveByOffset(100, 50)  // Move by x and y offset
       .release()
       .build()
       .perform();

4Ô∏è‚É£ Chaining Actions

You can chain multiple actions together:

actions.moveToElement(menu)
       .click(subMenu)
       .build()
       .perform();

5Ô∏è‚É£ Pro Tips

Always use build().perform() to execute the action.

For hover and dropdowns, combine Actions + Explicit Wait to wait for sub-menu visibility.

For drag-and-drop, offset coordinates can be useful for precise movements.

6Ô∏è‚É£ Interview-ready answer

‚ÄúIn Selenium, the Actions class is used for advanced user interactions like mouse hover, right click, double click, and drag-and-drop. You create an Actions object, define the action on a WebElement, chain actions if needed, and execute them using build().perform().‚Äù


What are Keyboard Actions?

Selenium provides the Actions class and sendKeys() method to simulate keyboard interactions.

Common uses:

Typing text

Pressing Enter, Tab, or Escape

Copy, paste, select all

Combining keys (Ctrl, Shift, Alt)

2Ô∏è‚É£ Using Actions class for keyboard actions
Step 1: Import Actions
import org.openqa.selenium.interactions.Actions;
import org.openqa.selenium.Keys;

Step 2: Create Actions object
Actions actions = new Actions(driver);

3Ô∏è‚É£ Common Keyboard Actions
A) Type text
WebElement input = driver.findElement(By.id("username"));
input.sendKeys("admin");  // simple typing

B) Press Enter / Tab / Escape
actions.sendKeys(input, Keys.ENTER).build().perform();  // Press Enter
actions.sendKeys(Keys.TAB).build().perform();           // Press Tab
actions.sendKeys(Keys.ESCAPE).build().perform();        // Press Escape

C) Keyboard shortcuts (Ctrl + A / C / V)
// Select all text
actions.keyDown(Keys.CONTROL).sendKeys("a").keyUp(Keys.CONTROL).build().perform();

// Copy
actions.keyDown(Keys.CONTROL).sendKeys("c").keyUp(Keys.CONTROL).build().perform();

// Paste
actions.keyDown(Keys.CONTROL).sendKeys("v").keyUp(Keys.CONTROL).build().perform();

D) Combine multiple keys
// Example: Ctrl + Shift + N (new window in Chrome)
actions.keyDown(Keys.CONTROL).keyDown(Keys.SHIFT).sendKeys("n").keyUp(Keys.SHIFT).keyUp(Keys.CONTROL).build().perform();

4Ô∏è‚É£ Using sendKeys() on WebElement directly

For simple inputs, you can also do:

driver.findElement(By.id("username")).sendKeys("admin" + Keys.TAB + "password" + Keys.ENTER);


This types text and presses keys in sequence.

5Ô∏è‚É£ Pro Tips

Use Actions class for advanced keyboard combinations.

Use sendKeys() on elements for simple typing and key presses.

Always use build().perform() with Actions to execute the action.

For dynamic inputs, combine Explicit Wait + sendKeys() to avoid ElementNotInteractableException.

6Ô∏è‚É£ Interview-ready answer

‚ÄúIn Selenium, keyboard actions can be handled using the Actions class or the sendKeys() method. sendKeys() can type text or simulate single keys like Enter or Tab, while Actions class can perform complex key combinations like Ctrl+C, Ctrl+V, or Shift+key. All actions in Actions class need to be executed with build().perform().‚Äù


Uploading Files via Input Box (<input type="file">)

Selenium can directly send the file path to the input element.

No need to click browse dialog ‚Äî it‚Äôs handled automatically.

Example HTML
<input type="file" id="uploadFile">

Selenium Code
WebElement upload = driver.findElement(By.id("uploadFile"));
upload.sendKeys("C:\\Users\\User\\Desktop\\file.txt");


Notes:

Provide absolute path of the file.

Works for all browsers.

After sendKeys(), the file is automatically selected and ready for submission.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Uploading Files via Non-Input Box (Custom Buttons)

Many modern websites use custom buttons (like drag & drop, or <div> triggers).

Selenium cannot interact directly because sendKeys() works only on <input type="file">.

Approaches:
A) Use AutoIT (Windows only)

AutoIT scripts interact with OS-level dialogs.

Steps:

Write an AutoIT script to handle the file upload window.

Compile it into an .exe.

Trigger the script from Selenium.

driver.findElement(By.id("customUploadButton")).click();
Runtime.getRuntime().exec("C:\\Scripts\\FileUpload.exe");

B) Use Robot Class (Java built-in)

java.awt.Robot simulates keyboard events.

Steps:

Click the custom button to open dialog.

Use Robot to type file path and press Enter.

driver.findElement(By.id("customUploadButton")).click();
Thread.sleep(2000);  // wait for dialog

StringSelection ss = new StringSelection("C:\\Users\\User\\Desktop\\file.txt");
Toolkit.getDefaultToolkit().getSystemClipboard().setContents(ss, null);

Robot robot = new Robot();
robot.keyPress(KeyEvent.VK_CONTROL);
robot.keyPress(KeyEvent.VK_V);
robot.keyRelease(KeyEvent.VK_V);
robot.keyRelease(KeyEvent.VK_CONTROL);
robot.keyPress(KeyEvent.VK_ENTER);
robot.keyRelease(KeyEvent.VK_ENTER);

C) JavaScript / jQuery Trigger

If the <input type="file"> is hidden (e.g., display:none), you can make it visible using JS, then sendKeys():

WebElement input = driver.findElement(By.cssSelector("input[type='file']"));
((JavascriptExecutor) driver).executeScript("arguments[0].style.display='block';", input);
input.sendKeys("C:\\Users\\User\\Desktop\\file.txt");

3Ô∏è‚É£ Key Differences
Feature	Input Box	Non-Input Box
Direct sendKeys()	‚úÖ Works	‚ùå Doesn‚Äôt work
OS Dialog Needed	‚ùå	‚úÖ Robot / AutoIT
JS Trick	Optional	Sometimes needed
Browser independent	‚úÖ	Robot is platform dependent
4Ô∏è‚É£ Interview-ready answer

‚ÄúFor file upload in Selenium, if the element is an <input type='file'>, you can directly use sendKeys() with the file path. For custom buttons or non-input elements, Selenium cannot interact directly, so we use OS-level automation like Robot class or AutoIT, or manipulate the hidden input via JavaScript and then use sendKeys().‚Äù

üí° Pro Tip:


What is the Robot Class?

java.awt.Robot is a Java built-in class used to generate native system events like:

Keyboard key press/release

Mouse move/click

Useful when Selenium cannot interact directly (e.g., OS-level dialogs, print dialogs, file download/upload dialogs).

Import:

import java.awt.Robot;
import java.awt.event.KeyEvent;

2Ô∏è‚É£ When to Use Robot Class

Uploading files when <input type="file"> is hidden

Downloading files where browser shows Save As dialog

Performing keyboard shortcuts like Ctrl+C, Ctrl+V

Handling print dialogs or alert pop-ups that are outside the browser

Selenium can only control browser DOM elements, not OS dialogs. Robot class bridges this gap.

3Ô∏è‚É£ How to Use Robot Class (Basic Example)
Step 1: Create Robot Object
Robot robot = new Robot();

Step 2: Press and release keys
robot.keyPress(KeyEvent.VK_CONTROL);  // Press CTRL
robot.keyPress(KeyEvent.VK_A);        // Press A (Select All)
robot.keyRelease(KeyEvent.VK_A);      // Release A
robot.keyRelease(KeyEvent.VK_CONTROL); // Release CTRL

Step 3: Type text (using clipboard)
// Copy file path to clipboard
StringSelection path = new StringSelection("C:\\Users\\User\\Desktop\\file.txt");
Toolkit.getDefaultToolkit().getSystemClipboard().setContents(path, null);

// Paste path in dialog
robot.keyPress(KeyEvent.VK_CONTROL);
robot.keyPress(KeyEvent.VK_V);
robot.keyRelease(KeyEvent.VK_V);
robot.keyRelease(KeyEvent.VK_CONTROL);

// Press Enter to submit
robot.keyPress(KeyEvent.VK_ENTER);
robot.keyRelease(KeyEvent.VK_ENTER);

4Ô∏è‚É£ How to Use Robot for File Download

Scenario: Browser opens Save As dialog (common in IE or when download is blocked).

Steps:

Click Download button in Selenium to open OS dialog.

Use Robot to:

Paste the file path in the Save As window

Press Enter to save

driver.findElement(By.id("downloadBtn")).click(); // Opens Save As

Robot robot = new Robot();
Thread.sleep(2000); // Wait for dialog

// Copy file path to clipboard
StringSelection filePath = new StringSelection("C:\\Users\\User\\Downloads\\report.pdf");
Toolkit.getDefaultToolkit().getSystemClipboard().setContents(filePath, null);

// Paste path
robot.keyPress(KeyEvent.VK_CONTROL);
robot.keyPress(KeyEvent.VK_V);
robot.keyRelease(KeyEvent.VK_V);
robot.keyRelease(KeyEvent.VK_CONTROL);

// Press Enter
robot.keyPress(KeyEvent.VK_ENTER);
robot.keyRelease(KeyEvent.VK_ENTER);


‚úÖ Tip: Always add a small Thread.sleep() to ensure the dialog appears before typing.

5Ô∏è‚É£ Advantages

Can interact with OS-level dialogs which Selenium cannot handle.

Works for keyboard shortcuts and mouse movements outside the browser.



Downloading Files via Direct Link Click

If clicking a link or button directly triggers a download (no popup), you can simply do:

driver.findElement(By.linkText("Download Report")).click();


Selenium will click the link, and the browser will start downloading the file to the default download folder.

Problem: You don‚Äôt control the file location or handle the dialog if the browser asks ‚ÄúSave As‚Äù.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Handling File Downloads in Chrome / Firefox

You can configure the browser profile to auto-download files to a specific folder.

A) Chrome
Step 1: Set Chrome options
import org.openqa.selenium.chrome.ChromeOptions;
import org.openqa.selenium.chrome.ChromeDriver;
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;

Map<String, Object> prefs = new HashMap<>();
prefs.put("download.default_directory", "C:\\Users\\User\\Downloads");
prefs.put("download.prompt_for_download", false); // Disable Save As dialog
prefs.put("profile.default_content_settings.popups", 0);

ChromeOptions options = new ChromeOptions();
options.setExperimentalOption("prefs", prefs);

WebDriver driver = new ChromeDriver(options);
driver.get("https://example.com");
driver.findElement(By.id("downloadBtn")).click();


Key points:

download.default_directory ‚Üí folder path where file will be saved.

download.prompt_for_download ‚Üí disables ‚ÄúSave As‚Äù popup.

Works for any file type Chrome supports.


Using TakesScreenshot Interface

TakesScreenshot is a Selenium interface implemented by WebDriver.

Steps to take a full-page screenshot:

Example
import org.openqa.selenium.TakesScreenshot;
import org.openqa.selenium.OutputType;
import org.openqa.selenium.io.FileHandler;
import java.io.File;

File src = ((TakesScreenshot) driver).getScreenshotAs(OutputType.FILE);
File dest = new File("C:\\Users\\User\\Desktop\\screenshot.png");
FileHandler.copy(src, dest);


Explanation:

getScreenshotAs(OutputType.FILE) ‚Üí captures screenshot and stores in temp file.

Copy the file to desired location using FileHandler.copy().

3Ô∏è‚É£ Screenshot of a Specific WebElement

You can capture only a particular element instead of the whole page:

WebElement element = driver.findElement(By.id("loginForm"));
File src = element.getScreenshotAs(OutputType.FILE);
File dest = new File("C:\\Users\\User\\Desktop\\element.png");
FileHandler.copy(src, dest);


Useful for highlighting errors in a specific section.




What is JavaScriptExecutor?

Selenium provides the JavascriptExecutor interface to run JavaScript code directly in the browser.

All WebDriver implementations (ChromeDriver, FirefoxDriver, etc.) support it.

Syntax:

JavascriptExecutor js = (JavascriptExecutor) driver;

2Ô∏è‚É£ When to Use JavaScriptExecutor

Clicking on elements that are not clickable due to overlay or hidden state.

Scrolling to specific elements or coordinates.

Fetching values or attributes not exposed in DOM.

Highlighting elements for testing/debugging.

Handling dynamic content or lazy-loaded elements.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Common JavaScriptExecutor Examples
A) Scroll Down / Scroll Into View
WebElement element = driver.findElement(By.id("footer"));

// Scroll to specific element
js.executeScript("arguments[0].scrollIntoView(true);", element);

// Scroll by pixels
js.executeScript("window.scrollBy(0, 500);");

B) Click on Hidden Element
WebElement hiddenButton = driver.findElement(By.id("hiddenBtn"));
js.executeScript("arguments[0].click();", hiddenButton);

C) Get Page Title / URL / Domain
String title = (String) js.executeScript("return document.title;");
String url = (String) js.executeScript("return document.URL;");
String domain = (String) js.executeScript("return document.domain;");

D) Enter Text in Input Box
WebElement input = driver.findElement(By.id("username"));
js.executeScript("arguments[0].value='admin';", input);

E) Highlight Element
WebElement element = driver.findElement(By.id("loginBtn"));
js.executeScript("arguments[0].style.border='3px solid red'", element);


Useful for debugging or visual confirmation during tests.

F) Refresh Page
js.executeScript("history.go(0)");

4Ô∏è‚É£ Full Syntax
JavascriptExecutor js = (JavascriptExecutor) driver;
js.executeScript("JavaScript code here", optional WebElements or arguments);


arguments[0] ‚Üí first WebElement passed

arguments[1] ‚Üí second WebElement passed, etc.

Can return values with return keyword.

5Ô∏è‚É£ Interview-ready answer

‚ÄúIn Selenium, the JavascriptExecutor interface allows you to execute JavaScript code directly in the browser. It is useful for clicking hidden elements, scrolling to elements, fetching page details, entering text, highlighting elements, or refreshing pages. You cast WebDriver to JavascriptExecutor and use executeScript() to run JavaScript commands.‚Äù





